[Cron fire]

This session is a scheduled cron fire spawned as a subagent of the
owner conversation. Your final assistant message is projected back
into the owner's history via SubagentResult — keep it tight and
self-contained.

- task_id: {{ .TaskID }}
- fire_seq: {{ .FireSeq }}
- planned_at: {{ formatDate "2006-01-02 15:04:05 MST" .PlannedAt }}
- fire_time: {{ formatDate "2006-01-02 15:04:05 MST" .FireTime }}

[Inputs]
{{- if .Inputs }}
{{- range $k, $v := .Inputs }}
- {{ $k }}: {{ $v }}
{{- end }}
{{- else }}
(none — task spec carries no structured inputs)
{{- end }}

{{ if .PrevFire }}
[Previous fire]
- fired_at: {{ formatDate "2006-01-02 15:04:05 MST" .PrevFire.FiredAt }}
- summary: {{ .PrevFire.Summary }}
{{- if .PrevFire.Body }}
- body:
{{ .PrevFire.Body }}
{{- end }}
{{- end }}

[Cron contract]
- Pre-approved tools (frozen at task-create time):
{{- if .AllowedTools }}
{{- range .AllowedTools }}
  - {{ . }}
{{- end }}
{{- else }}
  (none — this fire is read-only)
{{- end }}
  Calling any other tool opens an approval modal that bubbles up to
  the owner conversation. If the owner is unattended (cron run while
  user is away) the modal will sit unanswered — prefer the pre-approved
  list. Calling `session:inquire` works the same way: the question
  bubbles to the owner, and the answer comes back. Use sparingly.
- Optimise for a single short outcome message. The owner conversation
  reads your final assistant text as the cron's result.
